**EXHIBIT 31.1**
**SECTION 302 CERTIFICATION**
I, Andrew Rees, certify that:
1. I have reviewed this quarterly report on Form 10-Q of Crocs, Inc.;
2. Based on my knowledge, this report does not contain any untrue statement of a material fact or omit to state a material fact necessary to make the statements made, in light of the circumstances under which such statements were made, not misleading with respect to the period covered by this report;
3. Based on my knowledge, the financial statements, and other financial information included in this report, fairly present in all material respects the financial condition, results of operations and cash flows of the registrant as of, and for, the periods presented in this report;
4. The registrants other certifying officer(s) and I are responsible for establishing and maintaining disclosure controls and procedures (as defined in Exchange Act Rules 13a-15(e) and 15d-15(e)) and internal control over financial reporting (as defined in Exchange Act Rules 13a-15(f) and 15d-15(f)) for the registrant and have:
(a) Designed such disclosure controls and procedures, or caused such disclosure controls and procedures to be designed under our supervision, to ensure that material information relating to the registrant, including its consolidated subsidiaries, is made known to us by others within those entities, particularly during the period in which this report is being prepared;
(b) Designed such internal control over financial reporting, or caused such internal control over financial reporting to be designed under our supervision, to provide reasonable assurance regarding the reliability of financial reporting and the preparation of financial statements for external purposes in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles;
(c) Evaluated the effectiveness of the registrants disclosure controls and procedures and presented in this report our conclusions about the effectiveness of the disclosure controls and procedures, as of the end of the period covered by this report based on such evaluation; and
(d) Disclosed in this report any change in the registrants internal control over financial reporting that occurred during the registrants most recent fiscal quarter (the registrants fourth fiscal quarter in the case of an annual report) that has materially affected, or is reasonably likely to materially affect, the registrants internal control over financial reporting; and
5. The registrants other certifying officer(s) and I have disclosed, based on our most recent evaluation of internal control over financial reporting, to the registrants auditors and the audit committee of the registrants board of directors (or persons performing the equivalent functions):
(a) All significant deficiencies and material weaknesses in the design or operation of internal control over financial reporting which are reasonably likely to adversely affect the registrants ability to record, process, summarize and report financial information; and
(b) Any fraud, whether or not material, that involves management or other employees who have a significant role in the registrants internal control over financial reporting.
Date: July 29, 2014
/s/ Andrew Rees
Andrew Rees
__
_President_
_(Principal Executive Officer)_

us-gaap:FairValueInputsLevel1Member 2013-12-31 0001334036 2014-04-01 2014-06-30 0001334036 2013-04-01 2013-06-30 0001334036 2013-01-01 2013-06-30 0001334036 crox:MarketBasedRestrictedStockUnitsMember 2014-01-01 2014-06-30 0001334036 2014-06-30 0001334036 2013-12-31 0001334036 2014-01-01 2014-06-30 crox:segment iso4217:USD xbrli:shares iso4217:MXN crox:employee crox:store crox:item xbrli:pure xbrli:shares iso4217:USD 1339000 8722000 831000 500000 198000000 990 10513000 20837000 1900000 2200000 P1Y9M14D 13793100 61000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Beneficial conversion feature</font><font style="display: inline;"> &#x2013; The issuance of our Series A preferred stock generated a beneficial conversion feature, which arises when a debt or equity security is issued with an embedded conversion option that is beneficial to the investor or in the money at inception because the conversion option has an effective strike price that is less than the market price of the underlying stock at the commitment date. We recognize</font><font style="display: inline;background-color:yellow;">d the</font><font style="display: inline;"> beneficial conversion feature by allocating the intrinsic value of the conversion option, which is the number of common shares available upon conversion multiplied by the difference between the effective conversion price per share and the fair value of common stock per share on the commitment date, to additional paid-in capital, resulting in a discount on the Series A preferred stock. We will accrete the discount from the date of issuance through the redemption date of eight years following issuance. Accretion expense will be recognized as dividend equivalents over the eight year period utilizing the effective interest method.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 4900000 2500000 4900000 2500000 0 0 200000 100000 100000 100000 37870000 37870000 115846000 115846000 29.00 14.50 2015-12-01 2014-08-01 5176000 5434000 6940000 3985000 15800000 6 2900000 2300000 14100000 1500000 2200000 3200000 12565000 17482000 4100000 4100000 0 0 14300000 140455000 162890000 2000000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">16\. LEGAL PROCEEDINGS</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We and certain current and former officers and directors have been named as defendants in complaints filed by investors in the United States District Court for the District of Colorado. The first complaint was filed in November 2007 and several other complaints were filed shortly thereafter. These actions were consolidated and, in September 2008, the district court appointed a lead plaintiff and counsel. An amended consolidated complaint was filed in December 2008. The amended complaint purports to state claims under Sections&nbsp;10(b), 20(a), and 20A of the Exchange Act on behalf of a class of all persons who purchased our common stock between April&nbsp;2, 2007 and April&nbsp;14, 2008 (the "Class Period"). The amended complaint also added our independent auditor as a defendant. The amended complaint alleges that, during the Class Period, the defendants made false and misleading public statements about us and our business and prospects and, as a result, the market price of our common stock was artificially inflated. The amended complaint also claims that certain current and former officers and directors traded in our common stock on the basis of material non-public information. The amended complaint seeks compensatory damages on behalf of the alleged class in an unspecified amount, including interest, and also added attorneys' fees and costs of litigation. On February&nbsp;28, 2011, the District Court granted motions to dismiss filed by the defendants and dismissed all claims. A final judgment was thereafter entered. Plaintiffs subsequently appealed to the United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit. We and those current and former officers and directors named as defendants have entered into a Stipulation of Settlement with the plaintiffs that would, if approved by the United States District Court for the District of Colorado, resolve all claims asserted against us by the plaintiffs on behalf of the putative class, and plaintiffs' appeal would be dismissed. Our independent auditor is not a party to the Stipulation of Settlement. The Stipulation of Settlement received preliminary approval from the District Court on August&nbsp;28, 2013. It remains subject to customary conditions, including final court approval following notice to stockholders. On February&nbsp;13, 2014 a final settlement hearing took place and the parties are awaiting a ruling in conjunction with the same. If the settlement becomes final, all amounts required by the settlement will be paid by our insurers. There can be no assurance that the settlement will be finally approved by the District Court, or that approval by the District Court will, if challenged, be upheld by the Tenth Circuit.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On October 27, 2010, Spectrum Agencies (&#x201C;Spectrum&#x201D;) filed suit against our subsidiary, Crocs Europe B.V. (&#x201C;Crocs Europe&#x201D;), in the High Court of Justice, Queen&#x2019;s Bench Division, Royal Courts of Justice in London, United Kingdom (&#x201C;UK&#x201D;). Spectrum acted as an agent for Crocs products in the UK from 2005 until Crocs Europe terminated the relationship on July 3, 2008 due to Spectrum&#x2019;s breach of its duty to act in good faith towards Crocs Europe. Spectrum alleged that Crocs Europe unlawfully terminated the agency relationship and failed to pay certain sales commissions. A trial on the liability, not quantum (compensation and damages), was held at the High Court in London from November 30, 2011 to December 5, 2011. On December 16, 2011, the High Court of Justice issued a judgment that found that although Spectrum&#x2019;s actions were a breach of its duty to act in good faith towards Crocs Europe, the breach was not sufficiently severe to justify termination. We believed that the trial judge erred in his findings and subsequently appealed the judgment.&nbsp;&nbsp;On October 30, 2012, the Court of Appeal handed down its judgment which confirmed the trial judge&#x2019;s findings. We submitted a request to the Supreme Court seeking permission to appeal and on April 24, 2013, the Supreme Court declined our request.&nbsp;&nbsp;To that date the legal proceedings had only addressed liability, so there had been no findings in relation to the amount of compensation or damages, other than with respect to leg</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">al fees. On May 12, 2014, the parties agreed to settle the matter for</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> an amount within our accrual. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The parties have entered into a Consent Decree filed with the Court and we have made payment pursuant to the settlement agreement. The Compa</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ny</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> consider</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> this matter closed.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We are currently subject to an audit by U.S. Customs &amp; Border Protection (&#x201C;CBP&#x201D;) in respect of the period from 2006 to 2010.&nbsp;&nbsp;In October 2013, CBP issued a revised final audit report.&nbsp;In that report CBP projects that unpaid duties totaling approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">12.4</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million are due for the period under review (a reduction from </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$14.3</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million in the preliminary draft report issued in 2012).&nbsp;&nbsp;We have responded that these projections are erroneous and provided arguments that demonstrate the amount due in connection with this matter is considerably less than the projection.&nbsp; It is not possible at this time to predict whether our arguments will be successful in eliminating or reducing the amount in dispute.&nbsp;&nbsp;CBP has stated that the final report will recommend collection of the duties due.&nbsp;&nbsp;At this time, it is not possible to determine precisely when a notice of claim will be received from CBP, but currently we anticipate a notice of claim could be received sometime in the third quarter of 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Likewise, it is not possible to predict with any certainty whether CBP will seek to assert a claim for penalties in addition to any unpaid duties, but such an assertion is a possibility.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Mexico&#x2019;s Federal Tax Authority (&#x201C;SAT&#x201D;) audited the period from January 2006 to July 2011.&nbsp; There were two phases to the audit, the first for capital equipment and finished goods and the second for raw materials.&nbsp; The first phase was completed and no major discrepancies were noted by the SAT.&nbsp; On January 9, 2013, Crocs received a notice for the second phase in which the SAT issued a tax assessment (taxes and penalties) of roughly </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">280.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million pesos (approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">22.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million) based on the value of all of Crocs&#x2019; imported raw materials during the audit period.&nbsp; We believe that the proposed penalty amount</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> is unfounded and without merit. With the help of local counsel we filed an appeal by the deadline of March 15, 2013.&nbsp; We have argued that the amount due in connection with the matter, if any, is substantially less than that proposed by the SAT.&nbsp; In connection with the appeal, the SAT required us to post an appeal surety bond in the amount of roughly </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">321.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million pesos (approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">26.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million), which amount reflects estimated additional penalties and interest if we are not successful on our appeal.&nbsp; This amount will be adjusted on an annual basis. We expect it to take between two and three years for resolution of this matter in the Mexican courts.&nbsp; It is not possible at this time to predict the outcome of this matter or reasonably estimate any potential loss.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">As of June 30, 2014, we have accrued a total </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$3.7</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million relating to these litigation matters and other disputes. We estimate that the ultimate resolution of these litigation matters and other disputes could result in a loss that is reasonably possible between </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$0.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$9.6</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million in the aggregate, in excess of the amount accrued.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Although we are subject to other litigation from time to time in the ordinary course of business, including employment, intellectual property and product liability claims, we are not party to any other pending legal proceedings that we believe would reasonably have a material adverse impact on our business, financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:12pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 100 3500000 75 182200000 1803000 8667000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">9</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">. &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-weight:bold;">REVOLVING CREDIT FACILITY&nbsp;&amp; BANK BORROWINGS</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Revolving Credit Facility</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On </font><font style="display: inline;">December 16, 2011</font><font style="display: inline;">, we entered into a</font><font style="display: inline;">n Amended and Restated Credit Agreement</font><font style="display: inline;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">(</font><font style="display: inline;">as amended,</font><font style="display: inline;"> the &#x201C;Credit Agreement&#x201D;)</font><font style="display: inline;"> with the lenders named therein and P</font><font style="display: inline;">NC Bank, National Association (&#x201C;</font><font style="display: inline;">PNC</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x201D;</font><font style="display: inline;">), as a lender and admini</font><font style="display: inline;">strative agent for the lenders. </font><font style="display: inline;">The Credit Agreement enables us to borrow up to </font><font style="display: inline;">$100.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, with the ability to increase commitments to up to </font><font style="display: inline;">$125.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, subject to certain conditions, and is currently set to mature in December 2017. The Credit Agreement is available for working capital, capital expenditures, permitted acquisitions, reimbursement of drawings under letters of credit, and permitted dividends, distributions, purchases, redemptions and retirements of equity interests. Borrowings under the Credit Agreement are secured by all of our assets.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of </font><font style="display: inline;">June 30, 2014 and December 31, 2013</font><font style="display: inline;">, w</font><font style="display: inline;">e h</font><font style="display: inline;">ad </font><font style="display: inline;">no</font><font style="display: inline;"> outstanding borrowings under</font><font style="display: inline;"> the Credit Agreement. 2300000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">13</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">. SERIES A PREFERRED STOCK</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">On January&nbsp;27, 2014, we issued to </font><font style="display: inline;">Blacks</font><font style="display: inline;">tone Capital Partners VI&nbsp;L.P. (&#x201C;</font><font style="display: inline;">Blackstone</font><font style="display: inline;">&#x201D;</font><font style="display: inline;">)</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">, and certain of its permitted transferees (together with Blackstone, the &#x201C;Blackstone Purchasers&#x201D;), 200,000 shares of our Series&nbsp;A preferred stock for an aggregate purchase price of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">$198.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">&nbsp;million, or </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">$990</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> per share, pursuant to an Investment Agreement between us and Blackstone, dated December&nbsp;28, 2013 (as amended, the &#x201C;Investment Agreement&#x201D;). In connection with the issuance of the Series A preferred stock (the &#x201C;Closing&#x201D;), we received proceeds of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">$182.2</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> million after deducting the issuance discount of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">$2.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> million and direct and incremental expenses of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">$15.8</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> million including financial advisory fees, closing costs, legal expenses and other offering-related expenses.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Participation Rights and </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Dividends</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">The Series&nbsp;A preferred stock ranks senior to our common stock with respect to dividend rights and rights on liquidation, winding-up and dissolution. The Series&nbsp;A preferred stock has a stated value of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">$1,000</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> per share, and holders of Series&nbsp;A preferred stock are entitled to cumulative dividends payable quarterly in cash at a rate of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">6%</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> per annum. If we fail to make timely dividend payments, the dividend rate will increase to </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">8%</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> per annum until such time as all accrued but unpaid dividends have been paid in full. Holders of Series&nbsp;A preferred stock are entitled to receive dividends declared or paid on our common stock and are entitled to vote together with the holders of our common stock </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">as a single class, in each case, on an as-converted basis. As of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">June 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">, we had accrued dividends of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">$3.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> million on the condensed consolidated balance sheets, which were paid in cash to Blackstone on July 1, 2014. Holders of Series&nbsp;A preferred stock have c</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">ertain limited special approval rights, including with respect to the issuance of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">pari passu</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> or senior equity securities of the Company.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Conversion Features</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">The Series&nbsp;A preferred stock is convertible at the option of the holders at any time after the Closing into shares of common stock at an implied conversion price of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">$14.50</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> per share, subject to adjustment. At our election, all or a portion of the Series&nbsp;A preferred stock will be convertible into the relevant number of shares of common stock on or after the third anniversary of the Closing, if the closing price of the common stock equals or exceeds </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">$29.00</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> for 20 consecutive trading days. The Series A preferred stock is convertible into </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">13,793,100</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> shares of our common stock based on the conversio</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">n rate in place</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> as of June 30, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">. The conversion rate is subject to the following customary anti-dilution and other adjustments:</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:36pt;"><p style="width:36pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt; display: inline;"> <p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="margin:0pt;font-family:Symbol;font-size:10pt;;"> &#xB7;</font> </p> </td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top"> <p style="font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="display: inline;">If the Company has any stockholder rights plan in effect with respect to the common stock on the date of conversion, upon conversion of the Series A preferred stock, the holder will also receive (in addition to the common stock pursuant to the conversion) the rights under such rights plan, unless those rights (a) become exercisable before the conversion of the Series A preferred stock, or (b) are separated from the common stock (each a &#x201C;Trigger Event&#x201D;).&nbsp;&nbsp;Upon the occurrence of a Trigger Event, the Series A preferred stock conversion rate will be adjusted in accordance with 1) or 2) described above.</font></p></td></tr></table></div> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:36pt;"><p style="width:36pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt; Upon certain change of control events involving us, the holders can require us to repurchase the Series&nbsp;A preferred stock at 101% of the stated value thereof plus all accrued but unpaid dividends. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">In accordance with FASB ASC Topic 480-10-S99-3A, </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">SEC Staff Announcement: Classification and Measurement of Redeemable Securities</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">, redemption features which are not solely within the control of the issuer are required to be presented outside of permanent equity on the condensed consolidated balance sheets. inline;font-weight:bold;">. COMMITMENTS &amp; CONTINGENCIES</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Rental Commitments and Contingencies</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">We rent space for certain of our retail stores, offices, warehouses, vehicles, and equipment under operating leases expiring at various dates thro</font><font style="display: inline;">ugh 2033. C</font><font style="display: inline;">ertain leases contain rent escalation clauses (step rents) that require additional rental amounts in the later years of the term. Rent expense for leases with step rents or rent holidays is recognized on a straight-line basis over the lease term. Deferred rent is included in the </font><font style="display: inline;">condensed </font><font style="display: inline;">consolidated balance sheets in &#x2018;Accrued expenses and other current liabilities.&#x2019;</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The following table summarizes the composition of rent expense under operating leases for the three </font><font style="display: inline;">and six months ended June 30, 2014 and 2013</font><font style="display: inline;"> (in thousands):</font> </p> <div inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">8</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:10pt;">. DERIVATIVE FINANCIAL INSTRUMENTS </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">We transact business in various foreign countries and are therefore exposed to foreign currency exchange rate risk inherent in revenues, costs, and monetary assets and liabilities denominated in non-functional currencies. We have entered into foreign currency exchange forward contract</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> and currency swap derivative instruments to selectively protect against volatility in the value of non-functional currency denominated monetary assets and liabilities, and of future cash flows caused by changes in foreign currency exchange rates. We do not designate these derivative instruments as hedging instruments under the accounting standards for derivatives and hedging. Accordingly, these instruments are recorded at fair value as a derivative asset or liability on the balance sheet with their corresponding change in fair value rec</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ognized in &#x2018;Forei</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">gn currency transaction </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">losses, net&#x2019; in our condensed consolidated statements of income. For purposes of the condensed consolidated statement</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> of cash flows, we classify the cash flows at settlement from undesignated instruments in the same category as the cash flows from the related hedged items, generally within &#x2018;Cash provided by (used in) operating activities&#x2019;. See</font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;"> Note 7</font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;"> &#x2013; Fair Value Measurements</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> for further details regarding the fair values of the corresponding derivative assets and liab</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ilities.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> As of June 30</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, 2014, we did not have derivative assets or liabilities on our condensed consolidated balance sheets as all derivative forward contrac</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ts described in the table below were en</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">tered into on June 30</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, 2014.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The following table summarizes the notional amounts of the outstanding foreign currency exchange contracts at </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">June 30, 2014 and December 31, 2013</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">. The notional amounts of the derivative financial instruments shown below are denominated in their U</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">nited States (&#x201C;U.S.&#x201D;) D</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ollar equivalents and represent the amount of all contracts of the foreign currency specified. These notional values do not necessarily rep</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">resent amounts exchanged by the parties and, therefore, are not a direct measure of our exposure to the foreign currency exchange risks.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&nbsp;</font> </tr> </table></div> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Restricted Stock Awards and Units</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">From time to time, we grant </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">restricted stock awards (&#x201C;RSA&#x201D;) and restricted stock units (&#x201C;RSU&#x201D;)</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to our </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">employees. R</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">SAs and RSUs </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">generally vest over three or four years depending on the terms of the grant.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Unvested RSAs have the same rights as those of common shares including voting rights and non-forfeitable dividend rights. However, ownership of unvested RSAs cannot be transferred until they are ve</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">sted. An unvested RSU is a contractual right to receive a share of common stock only upon its vesting. RSUs have dividend equivalent rights which accrue over the term of the award and are paid if and when the RSUs vest, but they have no voting rights.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">We typically grant time-based RSUs and performance-based RSUs. Time-based RSUs are typically granted on an annual basis to certain non-executive employees and vest in three annual installments on a straight-line basis beginning one year after the grant date. During the three months ended June 30, 2014 and 2013, the board of directors did not approve the grant of a material amount of</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> time-based RSUs to non-executives. </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">D</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">uring the six months ended June 30, 2014 and 2013, the board of dire</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">ctors approved </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">0.3</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;million </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">grants of time-based</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> RSU</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">s to non-executives</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">. &nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">Performance-based RSUs are typically grante</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">d on an annual basis to </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">executive</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">s</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> and consist of a time-based a</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">nd performance-based component. </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">Dur</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">ing </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">the three months ended June 30</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">, 201</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">4 and 2013, the board of directors </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">did not approve any grants of </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">RSU</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">s to executives as part of a performance incentive program. </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">Dur</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">ing the six months ended June 30, 201</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">4 and 2013, the board of directors approved the grant of an aggregate of </font><font style="display: and </font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;">0.7</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;font-size:10pt;"> million, respectively, </font><font inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -18pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Appointment of President</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-indent: -18pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;background-color:yellow;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On May 13, 2014, the board of directors appointed Andrew Rees as President of the Company, effective June 9, 2014.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">Upon the commencement of his employment, </font><font style="display: inline;">Mr. Rees was granted a market-based RSU with a maximum value of </font><font style="display: inline;">$3.5</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, which shall vest based on the achievement of certain share price levels on or before the fourth anniversary of his start date, subject to continued employment with the Company. </font><font style="display: inline;">This grant represents the right to receive </font><font style="display: inline;">0.2</font><font style="display: inline;"> million shares of the Company&#x2019;s common stock based on the 30-day volume-weighted average price of </font><font style="display: inline;">$15.02</font><font style="display: inline;"> per share immediately prior to his appointment. Based on a Monte-Carlo valuation model, the fair value of the RSU was determined to be </font><font style="display: inline;">$2.3</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, or </font><font style="display: inline;">65.7%</font><font style="display: inline;"> of the grant price, which will be expensed on a straight-line basis over a derived service period of </font><font style="display: inline;">1.788</font><font style="display: inline;"> years.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 3033000 0.73 0.40 0.26 0.19 0.72 0.40 0.25 0.19 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Earnings per share</font><font style="display: inline;"> \- Basic and diluted earnings per common share (&#x201C;EPS&#x201D;) is presented using the two-class method, which is an earnings allocation formula that determines earnings per share for common stock and any participating securities according to dividend rights and participation rights in undistributed earnings. Under the two-class method, EPS is computed by dividing the sum of distributed and undistributed earnings attributable to common stockholders by the weighted average number of shares of common stock outstanding during the period. A participating security is a security that may participate in undistributed earnings with common stock had those earnings been distributed in any form. Our recently issued Series A preferred stock represent participating securities as holders of the Series A preferred stock are entitled to receive any and all dividends declared or paid on common stock on an as-converted basis. In addition, shares of our non-vested restricted stock awards are considered participating securities as they represent unvested share-based payment awards containing non-forfeitable rights to dividends. As such, these participating securities must be included in the computation of EPS pursuant to the two-class method on a pro-rata, as-converted basis. Diluted EPS reflects the potential dilution from securities that could share in our earnings. In addition, the dilutive effect of each participating security is calculated using the more dilutive of the two-class method described above, which assumes that the securities remain in their current form, or the if-converted method, which assumes conversion to common stock as of the beginning of the reporting date. Anti-dilutive securities are excluded from diluted EPS. See </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Note 12&#x2014;Earnings Per Share</font><font style="display: inline;"> for further discussion.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">12</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">. Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The majority </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">of our non-financial instrument assets</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, which include inventories, property and equipment and intangible assets, are not required to be carried at fair value on a recurring basis. These</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;"> charges were related to certain obsolete footwear in the Other businesses segment an</font><font style="display: inline;font-family:Times;">d are reported in cost of sales in the condensed consolidated statements of income.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 154272000 184748000 162341000 191648000 7384000 6395000 685000 505000 2029000 823000 517000 880000 403000 93235000 102615000 7200000 7400000 250415000 306689000 875159000 1101873000 186928000 255160000 0 100000000 125000000 3700000 16800000 14400000 11670000 9040000 5100000 5400000 5404000 313000 3374000 5340000 9600000 0 52003000 53582000 -8112000 131131000 -32259000 -31065000 37741000 -16979000 64317000 35356000 32401000 23277000 64317000 35356000 25896000 19523000 4 88069000 25023000 155957000 -9412000 43818000 62788000 24328000 30000 -58506000 50419000 17463000 87810000 -5535000 23005000 35685000 11657000 15000 -31871000 58733000 20330000 139830000 -8345000 38357000 61578000 19565000 30000 -72782000 41911000 13868000 84709000 -4589000 24920000 33895000 12026000 15000 -38224000 9644000 7148000 9684000 7261000 49044000 24776000 55649000 28110000 58378000 31768000 64886000 35128000 310000 156000 447000 243000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">1\. GENERAL</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Organization</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Crocs,&nbsp;Inc. and its subsidiaries (collectively the &#x201C;Company,&#x201D; &#x201C;we,&#x201D; &#x201C;our&#x201D; or &#x201C;us&#x201D;) are engaged in the design, development, manufacturing, marketing and distribution of footwear, apparel and accessories for men, women and children.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Basis of Presentation</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The accompanying unaudited condensed consolidated financial statements have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States (&#x201C;GAAP&#x201D;) for interim financial information and with the rules&nbsp;and regulations of the Securities and Exchange Commission (&#x201C;SEC&#x201D;) for reporting on Form&nbsp;10-Q. The condensed consolidated balance sheet as of December 31, 2013 was derived from the Company&#x2019;s Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December 31, 2013 (the &#x201C;2013 Form 10-K&#x201D;). Accordingly, these statements do not include all of the information and disclosures required by GAAP or SEC rules&nbsp;and regulations for complete financial statements. In the opinion of management, these financial statements reflect all adjustments (consisting solely of normal recurring matters) considered necessary for a fair presentation of the results for the interim periods presented. The results of operations for any interim period are not necessarily indicative of results for the full year.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In t</font><font style="display: inline;">he accompanying condensed consolidated balance sheet</font><font style="display: inline;">s</font><font style="display: inline;"> as of June 30, 2014, </font><font style="display: inline;">we</font><font style="display: inline;"> recorded an out-of-period adjustment related to the calculation of a beneficial conversion feature associated with the issuance of the Series A </font><font style="display: inline;">convertible </font><font style="display: inline;">preferred stock </font><font style="display: inline;">(&#x201C;Series A preferred stock&#x201D;) on January 27, 2014. </font><font style="display: inline;">This adjustment was a non-cash adjustment and had no effect on operating income. The adjustment decreased the previously reported balance of the Series A preferred stock and increased the previously reported balance of additional paid-i</font><font style="display: inline;">n capital by approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">$12.3</font><font style="display: inline;"> million.&nbsp;The adjustment did not have a material impact on </font><font style="display: inline;">our</font><font style="display: inline;"> condensed consolidated st</font><font style="display: inline;">atements of income for the three </font><font style="display: inline;">months ended March 31, 2014, and there was no impact on </font><font style="display: inline;">our</font><font style="display: inline;"> condensed consolidated statements of comp</font><font style="display: inline;">rehensive income or cash flows for the three </font><font style="display: inline;">months ended March 31, 2014.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Reclassifications</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Certain prior period amounts on the condensed consolidated financial statements have been reclassified to conform to current period presentation. We segregated certain restructuring charges recorded to selling, general and administrative expenses on the condensed consolidated statements of income during the three months ended March 31, 2014 to the restructuring charges line item on the condensed consolidated statements of income during the six months ended June 30, 2014. In addition, we segregated certain accrued restructuring charges recorded to accrued expenses and other liabilities on the condensed consolidated balance sheets at March 31, 2014 and changes in accrued expenses and other liabilities on the condensed consolidated statements of cash flows for the three months ended March 31, 2014 to the accrued restructuring line item on the condensed consolidated balance sheets at June 30, 2014 and changes in accrued restructuring on the condensed consolidated statements of cash flows for the six months ended June 30, 2014. These reclassifications had no effect on income from operations, current liabilities or cash provided by (used in) operating activities.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Summary of Significant Accounting Policies</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">These statements should be read in conjunction with the consolidated financial statements and footnotes included in the 2013 Form 10-K. The accounting policies used in preparing these unaudited condensed consolidated financial statements are the same as those described in </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Note 1 &#x2014; Organization &amp; Summary of Significant Accounting Policies</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to the consolidated financial statements in the 2013 Form 10-K.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Earnings per share</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> \- Basic and diluted earnings per common share (&#x201C;EPS&#x201D;) is presented using the two-class method, which is an earnings allocation formula that determines earnings per share for common stock and any participating securities according to dividend rights and participation rights in undistributed earnings. Under the two-class method, EPS is computed by dividing the sum of distributed and undistributed earnings attributable to common stockholders by the weighted average number of shares of common stock outstanding during the period. A participating security is a security that may participate in undistributed earnings with common stock had those earnings been distributed in any form. Our recently issued Series A preferred stock represent participating securities as holders of the Series A preferred stock are entitled to receive any and all dividends declared or paid on common stock on an as-converted basis. In addition, shares of our non-vested restricted stock awards are considered participating securities as they represent unvested share-based payment awards containing non-forfeitable rights to dividends. As such, these participating securities must be included in the computation of EPS pursuant to the two-class method on a pro-rata, as-converted basis. Diluted EPS reflects the potential dilution from securities that could share in our earnings. In addition, the dilutive effect of each participating security is calculated using the more dilutive of the two-class method described above, which assumes that the securities remain in their current form, or the if-converted method, which assumes conversion to common stock as of the beginning of the reporting date. Anti-dilutive securities are excluded from diluted EPS. See </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Note 12&#x2014;Earnings Per Share</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> for further discussion.</font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Beneficial conversion feature</font><font style="display: inline;"> &#x2013; The issuance of our Series A preferred stock generated a beneficial conversion feature, which arises when a debt or equity security is issued with an embedded conversion option that is beneficial to the investor or in the money at inception because the conversion option has an effective strike price that is less than the market price of the underlying stock at the commitment date. We recognize</font><font style="display: inline;background-color:yellow;">d the</font><font style="display: inline;"> beneficial conversion feature by allocating the intrinsic value of the conversion option, which is the number of common shares available upon conversion multiplied by the difference between the effective conversion price per share and the fair value of common stock per share on the commitment date, to additional paid-in capital, resulting in a discount on the Series A preferred stock. We will accrete the discount from the date of issuance through the redemption date of eight years following issuance. Accretion expense will be recognized as dividend equivalents over the eight year period utilizing the effective interest method.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Recently Issued Accounting Standards</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;background-color:yellow;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;text-decoration:underline;">Discontinued Operations</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In April 2014, the </font><font style="display: inline;">Financial Accounting Standards Board (&#x201C;FASB&#x201D;) </font><font style="display: inline;">issued Accounting Standards Update (&#x201C;ASU&#x201D;) No. 2014-08: </font><font style="font-style:italic;display: inline;">Presentation of Financial Statements (Topic 205) and Property, Plant, and Equipment (Topic 360): Reporting Discontinued Operations and Disclosures of Disposals of Components of an Entity</font><font style="display: inline;">, which amends the definition of a discontinued operation in ASC 205-20 and requires entities to provide additional disclosures about discontinued operations as well as disposal transactions that do not meet the discontinued-operations criteria. The FASB issued the ASU to provide more decision-useful information and to make it more difficult for a disposal transaction to qualify as a discontinued operation. Under the previous guidance, the results of operations of a component of an entity were classified as a discontinued operation if all of the following conditions were met:</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:18pt;"><p style="width:18pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt; display: inline;"> <p style="border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="margin:0pt;font-family:Symbol;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9;font-size:10pt;;"> &#xB7;</font> </p> </td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top"> <p style="border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="display: inline;">The component has been disposed of or is classified as held for sale.</font></p></td></tr></table></div> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:18pt;"><p style="width:18pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt; display: inline;"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="margin:0pt;font-family:Symbol;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9;font-size:10pt;;"> &#xB7;</font> </p> </td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="display: inline;">The operations and cash flows of the component have been (or will be) eliminated from the ongoing operations of the entity as a result of the disposal transaction.</font></p></td></tr></table></div> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:18pt;"><p style="width:18pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt; display: inline;"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="margin:0pt;font-family:Symbol;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9;font-size:10pt;;"> &#xB7;</font> </p> </td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="display: inline;">The entity will not have any significant continuing involvement in the operations of the component after the disposal transaction.</font></p></td></tr></table></div> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The new guidance eliminates the second and third criteria above and instead requires discontinued o</font><font style="display: inline;">perations treatment for disposal</font><font style="display: inline;">s of a component or group of components that represents a strategic shift that has or will have a major impact on an entity&#x2019;s operations or financial results. The ASU also expands the scope of ASC 205-20 to disposals of equity method investments and businesses that, upon initial acquisition, qualify as held for sale. </font><font style="display: inline;">In addition, the ASU requires entities to reclassify assets and liabilities of a discontinued operation for all comparative periods presented in the statement of financial position. Before these amendments, ASC 205-20 neither required nor prohibited such presentation.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">Regarding the statement of cash flows, an entity must disclose, in all periods presented, either (1) operating and investing cash flows or (2) depreciation and amortization, capital expenditures, and significant operating and investing noncash items related to the discontinued operation. This presentation requirement represents a significant change from previous guidance. This ASU is effective prospectively for all disposals or components initially classified as held for sale in periods beginning on or after December 15, 2014. </font><font style="display: inline;">Early adoption is permitted. </font><font style="display: inline;">The Company does not anticipate this pronouncement to have a material impact to the Company&#x2019;s consolidated financial </font><font style="display: inline;">statements</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;text-decoration:underline;">Revenue Recognition</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In May 2014, the FASB issued their final standard on revenue from contracts with customers. The standard, issued as ASU No. 2014-09: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Revenue from Contracts with Customers</font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">(Topic 606)</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">by the FASB, outlines a single comprehensive model for entities to use in accounting for revenue arising from contracts with customers and supersedes most current revenue recognition guidance, including industry-specific guidance. The core principle of the revenue model is that &#x201C;an entity recognizes revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services.&#x201D; In applying the revenue model to contracts within its scope, an entity:</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:18pt;"><p style="width:18pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt; display: inline;"> <p style="border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="margin:0pt;font-family:Symbol;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9;font-size:10pt;;"> &#xB7;</font> </p> </td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top"> <p style="border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="display: inline;">Identifies the contr</font><font style="display: inline;">act(s) with a customer (Step 1)</font></p></td></tr></table></div> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:18pt;"><p style="width:18pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt; display: inline;"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="margin:0pt;font-family:Symbol;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9;font-size:10pt;;"> &#xB7;</font> </p> </td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="display: inline;">Identifies the performance oblig</font><font style="display: inline;">ations in the contract (Step 2)</font></p></td></tr></table></div> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:18pt;"><p style="width:18pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt; display: inline;"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="margin:0pt;font-family:Symbol;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9;font-size:10pt;;"> &#xB7;</font> </p> </td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="display: inline;">Determines</font><font style="display: inline;"> the transaction price (Step 3)</font></p></td></tr></table></div> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:18pt;"><p style="width:18pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt; display: inline;"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="margin:0pt;font-family:Symbol;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9;font-size:10pt;;"> &#xB7;</font> </p> </td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="display: inline;">Allocates the transaction price to the performance oblig</font><font style="display: inline;">ations in the contract (Step 4)</font></p></td></tr></table></div> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:18pt;"><p style="width:18pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt; display: inline;"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="margin:0pt;font-family:Symbol;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9;font-size:10pt;;"> &#xB7;</font> </p> </td><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td align="left" valign="top"> <p style="border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt;margin:0pt;"> <font style="display: inline;">Recognizes revenue when (or as) the entity satisfies a perfor</font><font style="display: inline;">mance obligation (Step 5)</font></p></td></tr></table></div> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The ASU applies to all contracts with customers except those that are within the scope of other topics in the FASB Accounting Standards Codification. Certain of the ASU&#x2019;s provisions also apply to transfers of nonfinancial assets, including in-substance nonfinancial assets that are not an output of an entity&#x2019;s ordinary</font><font style="display: inline;"> activities (e.g., sales of </font><font style="display: inline;">prop</font><font style="display: inline;">erty, plant, and equipment, real estate or </font><font style="display: inline;">intangible assets).</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">Existing accounting guidan</font><font style="display: inline;">ce applicable to these transfers </font><font style="display: inline;">has been amended or superseded. Compared with current U.S. GAAP, the ASU also requires significantly expanded disclosures about revenue recognition.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;background-color:yellow;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">T</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">he ASU is effective for annual reporting periods (including interim reporting periods within those periods) beginning after December 15, 2016. Early application is not permitted</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">. &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The Company </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">is currently evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">the Company&#x2019;s consolidated financial </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">statements</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 6513000 6475000 53661000 40983000 -3000 0 0 0 10567000 6250000 759000 -221000 15201000 16745000 -733000 -732000 -167000 -195000 171000 30000 679000 619000 243000 127000 3543000 2683000 12533000 47005000 -1922000 -403000 -1410000 -109000 2134000 0 15800000 256000 787000 11833000 18944000 19676000 11376000 5166000 3033000 0.001 0.001 5000000 5000000 0 0 29175000 37923000 1439000 1209000 182220000 14572000 545000 43000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">3\. PROPERTY &amp; EQUIPMENT</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The following table summarizes property and equipment by major classification as of </font><font style="display: inline;">June 30, 2014 and December 31, 2013</font><font style="display: inline;">:</font> </p> <div style="width:100%"><table cellpadding="0" Roman;height:1.00pt;overflow:hidden;font-size:0pt;"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:1pt;">&nbsp;</font></p> </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:01.76%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 Roman;height:1.00pt;overflow:hidden;font-size:0pt;"> &nbsp;</p> </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:02.82%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: #auto;height:1.00pt;padding:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;height:1.00pt;overflow:hidden;font-size:0pt;"> &nbsp;</p> </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:20.64%;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-left:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-right:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;background-color: <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Machinery and equipment</font></p> </td> <td valign="bottom" style="width:01.76%;border-top:1pt none style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">6\. RESTRUCTURING ACTIVITIES</font> </p> <p style="margin:4.5pt 0pt 0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Restructuring</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;background-color:yellow;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On July 21, 2014, we announced strategic plans for long-term improv</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ement and growth of the business. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">These plans comprise four</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> key initiatives including: (1) s</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">treamlining the global product and marketing portfolio, (2) reducing direct investment in smaller geographic markets, (3) creating a more efficient organizational structure including reducing duplicative and excess overhead which will also enhance the decision making process, and (4) closing or converting approx</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">imately </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">75</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">100</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> retail location</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s around the world.</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> The initial effects of these plans were incurred in the first and second quarter of 2014 and are expected to continue for the next 18 months. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">As a result, the Company recorded restructuring charges of $4.1 million and $6.3 million during the three and six months ended June 30, 2014, respectively. We are </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">unable in good faith to determine the type of cost</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;background-color:yellow;">we</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> will incur in connection with this </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">strategic restructuring </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">plan or to estimate the total amount or range of amounts expected to be incurred in connection with this plan for each major type of cost associated with this </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">strategic restructuring plan.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none 0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">As mentioned above, the Company plans to close 75 to 100 retail locations around the globe. As such, we expect to incur certain exit costs specific to store closures including operating lease termination costs, rent obligations for leased facilities, net of expected sublease income, and other expenses in association with this plan. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">During the three and six months ended June 30, 2014, we closed seven and nine </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">company-operated </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">retail locations, respectively, which were not scheduled to close until future periods and were selected for closure by management based on historical and projected profitability levels, relocation plans, and other factor</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">s.
